Portfolio
AOL Time Warner Headquarters
Ken Lippmann, Jr.

Just 17 blocks north of Times Square, on the South West corner of Central Park, also known as Columbus Circle, 4 giant tower cranes have slowly been inching there way toward the sky to top off two adjoining towers -each 75 stories tall - to create the new home for the AOL Time Warner headquarters.

Since the start of the project, Kenseal has been working with all the major sub-contractors involved for Bovis Lend Lease. Starting with the foundation, excavation and concrete were done by Mayrich Construction while waterproofing was performed by Construction Waterproofing. The waterproofing material at the time was new to the market.  Over 200,000 sq. ft. of Grace Construction Products' Prepruf, Bituthane, and Hydroduct accessory products were applied to the concrete foundation.

As the steel was erected, next came the glass and metal curtain wall, manufactured by Glasalum International in Miami and erected here in New York by Diamond Installations.  Final field glazing was performed by R.S.G. Caulking and Waterproofing, and again assisted by Kenseal with multiple products starting with Dow Corning silicones and butyl caulk and tapes by Pecora.

While the superstructure was being constructed many other specialty contractors were involved - W & W Glass Systems constructed a large atrium between the 2 towers, and the first 4 stories required massive storefront work constructed by J.E.M. Architectural. In all, there is over 1 million square feet of glass and metal to be glazed and sealed with Dow Corning Silicones. Outside of the glass and metal work, there is an interior parking garage that will be coated with Vulkem urethane deck coatings applied by Eagle One Roofing Contractors. Kenseal wants to thank all of the above contractors for getting us involved with such a large project right in the middle of Manhattan.
